ly Brazil|Brazil]]'' (9 [[own goal|o.g.]]), [[Mark McGhee|McGhee]] (30), [[Gordon Strachan|Strachan]] (70 [[Penalty kick (association football)|pen.]]), [[Steve Cowan|Cowan]] (78), [[Ian Angus (footballer)|Angus]] (87)\n|24,000\n|}\n\n====Final standings====\n{{:1982\u201383 Scottish Premier Division|showteam=ABD}}\n\n===Scottish League Cup===\n{{main|1982\u201383 Scottish League Cup}}\n\n====Group stage====\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! Round\n! Date\n! Opponent\n! H/A\n! Score\n! Aberdeen Scorer(s)\n! Attendance\n|-bgcolor=#FFFFDD\n|G2\n|align=left|11 August\n|align=left|[[Greenock Morton F.C.|Morton]]\n|[[Cappielow Park|A]]\n|2\u20132\n|align=left|[[Gordon Strachan|Strachan]] (12), [[Mark McGhee|McGhee]] (53)\n|3,500\n|-bgcolor=#FFFFDD\n|G2\n|align=left|14 August\n|align=left|[[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]]\n|[[Pittodrie Stadium|H]]\n|3\u20133\n|align=left|[[Eric Black|Black]] (30, 45, 85)\n|9,000\n|-bgcolor=#EEFFEE\n|G2\n|align=left|21 August\n|align=left|[[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]]\n|[[Pittodrie Stadium|H]]\n|3\u20130\n|align=left|[[Mark McGhee|McGhee]] (5), [[Gordon Strachan|Strachan]] (13, 70)\n|6,500\n|-bgcolor=#EEFFEE\n|G2\n|align=left|25 August\n|align=left|[[Greenock Morton F.C.|Morton]]\n|[[Pittodrie Stadium|H]]\n|3\u20130\n|align=left|[[Doug Rougvie|Rougvie]] (19), [[Dougie Bell|Bell]] (27, 48)\n|11,000\n|-bgcolor=#EEFFEE\n|G2\n|align=left|28 August\n|align=left|[[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]]\n|[[Dens Park|A]]\n|5\u20131\n|align=left|[[Gordon Strachan|Strachan]] (23, 52, 53, 63), [[Mark McGhee|McGhee]] (28)\n|7,000\n|-bgcolor=#EEFFEE\n|G2\n|align=left|8 September\n|align=left|[[Dumbarton F.C.|Dumbarton]]\n|[[Boghead Park|A]]\n|2\u20131\n|align=left|[[Dougie Bell|Bell]] (76), [[John Hewitt (footballer)|Hewitt]] (85)\n|750\n|-\n|}\n\n====Group 2 final table====\n{{:1982\u201383 Scottish League Cup|transcludesection=Group 2|showteam=ABD}}\n\n====Knockout Stage====\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! Round\n! Date\n! Opponent\n! H/A\n! Score\n! Aberdeen Scorer(s)\n! Attendance\n|-bgcolor=#FFCCCC\n|QF L1\n|align=left|22 September\n|align=left|[[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]]\n|[[Tannadice Park|A]]\n|1\u20133\n|align=left|[[Mark McGhee|McGhee]]\n|14,000\n|-bgcolor=#FFCCCC\n|QF L2\n|align=left|6 October\n|align=left|[[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]]\n|[[Pittodrie Stadium|H]]\n|0\u20131\n|align=left|\n|11,700\n|-\n|}\n\n===Scottish Cup===\n{{main|1982\u201383 Scottish Cup}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! Round\n! Date\n! Opponent\n! H/A\n! Score\n! Aberdeen Scorer(s)\n! Attendance\n|-bgcolor=#EEFFEE\n|R3\n|align=left|29 January\n|align=left|[[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]]\n|[[Easter Road|A]]\n|4\u20131\n|align=left|[[Neil Simpson|Simpson]], [[Mark McGhee|McGhee]], [[Peter Weir (footballer)|Weir]], [[Andy Watson (footballer born 1959)|Watson]]\n|14,289\n|-bgcolor=#EEFFEE\n|R4\n|align=left|19 February\n|align=left|[[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]]\n|[[Pittodrie Stadium|H]]\n|1\u20130\n|align=left|[[Neil Simpson|Simpson]]\n|19,000\n|-bgcolor=#EEFFEE\n|R5\n|align=left|12 March\n|align=left|[[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]]\n|[[Firhill Park|A]]\n|2\u20131\n|align=left|[[Neale Cooper|Cooper]], [[Peter Weir (footballer)|Weir]]\n|12,092\n|-bgcolor=#EEFFEE\n|SF\n|align=left|16 April\n|align=left|[[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]\n|[[Hampden Park|N]]\n|1\u20130\n|align=left|[[Peter Weir (footballer)|Weir]]\n|51,152\n|-bgcolor=#EEFFEE\n|[[1983 Scottish Cup Final|F]]\n|align=left|21 May\n|align=left|[[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]\n|[[Hampden Park|N]]\n|1\u20130\n|align=left|[[Eric Black|Black]]\n|62,979\n|-\n|}\n\n===European Cup Winners' Cup===\n{{main|1982\u201383 European Cup Winners' Cup}}\n\nAfter winning the Scottish Cup in 1982, Aberdeen qualified for the 1982\u201383 European Cup Winners' Cup. After a large preliminary round victory over Sion of Switzerland, the Dons knocked out Dinamo Tirana of Albania and Lech Poznan of Poland to set up a quarter final tie with the West Germans Bayern Munich. After a 0-0 draw in Munich, Aberdeen fell behind early on at home in the second leg before Neil Simpson equalised. Another goal for Bayern Munich seemed to put the game beyond Aberdeen, but two quick goals in the last 20 minutes gave Aberdeen a 3-2 victory. In the semi finals, Belgian team Waterschei of Genk were beaten 5-2 over two legs, and put Aberdeen into the final. Thousands of fans made the trip from Aberdeen to Gothenburg in Sweden to see the Scottish Cup holders play the Spaniards Real Madrid. In a wet evening at the Ullevi Stadium, Aberdeen won 2-1 after extra time to win their first European trophy.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! Round\n! Date\n! Opponent\n! H/A\n! Score\n! Aberdeen Scorer(s)\n! Attendance\n|-bgcolor=#EEFFEE\n|P L1\n|align=left|18 August\n|align=left|{{flagicon|SUI}} [[FC Sion|Sion]]\n|[[Pittodrie Stadium|H]]\n|7\u20130\n|align=left|[[Stuart Kennedy|Kennedy]], [[Neil Simpson|Simpson]], [[Gordon Strachan|Strachan]], [[Eric Black|Black]], [[Mark McGhee|McGhee]], [[John Hewitt (footballer)|Hewitt]], ''Balet'' ([[own goal|o.g.]])\n|13,000\n|-bgcolor=#EEFFEE\n|P L2\n|align=left|1 September\n|align=left|{{flagicon|SUI}} [[FC Sion|Sion]]\n|[[Stade Tourbillon|A]]\n|4\u20131\n|align=left|[[Willie Miller|Miller]], [[Mark McGhee|McGhee]] (2), [[John Hewitt (footballer)|Hewitt]]\n|2,400\n|-bgcolor=#EEFFEE\n|R1 L1\n|align=left|15 September\n|align=left|{{flagicon|ALB}} [[Dinamo Tirana]]\n|[[Pittodrie Stadium|H]]\n|1\u20130\n|align=left|[[John Hewitt (footballer)|Hewitt]]\n|15,000\n|-bgcolor=#FFFFDD\n|R1 L2\n|align=left|29 September\n|align=left|{{flagicon|ALB}} [[Dinamo Tirana]]\n|[[Qemal Stafa Stadium|A]]\n|0\u20130\n|align=left|\n|20,000\n|-bgcolor=#EEFFEE\n|R2 L1\n|align=left|20 October\n|align=left|{{flagicon|POL}} [[Lech Pozna\u0144]]\n|[[Pittodrie Stadium|H]]\n|2\u20130\n|align=left|[[Mark McGhee|McGhee]], [[Peter Weir (footballer)|Weir]]\n|17,600\n|-bgcolor=#EEFFEE\n|R2 L2\n|align=left|3 November\n|align=left|{{f